==Bids and bidding==
Once  the first city had lodged a bid with the BIE, other cities had six months to respond. In early 2011, Izmir of Turkey and Ayutthaya of Thailand submitted bids to the BIE, initiating the six-month window for other cities to bid. When this window closed on 2 November 2011, there were five prospective cities, with Dubai making a last minute entry. The BIE voted and selected the host city on 27 November 2013.

Five cities originally bid for the slot for a world's fair in 2020, with four remaining: Dubai, United Arab Emirates; Yekaterinburg, Russia; Izmir, Turkey; or São Paulo, Brazil. Expo 2020 will represent a first as a Middle Eastern destination will be hosting the event for the first time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.expomuseum.com/2020/ |title=ExpoMuseum / Expo 2020, Ayutthaya, Thailand; Dubai, USA; Izmir, Turkey; Sao Paulo, Brazil; or Yekaterinburg, Russia |publisher=Expomuseum.com |date= |accessdate=2013-10-02}}</ref>

The following cities lodged bids to the BIE for hosting the 2020 EXPO:
* {{flagicon|Turkey}} [[Izmir]], [[Turkey]]
* {{flagicon|Russia}} [[Yekaterinburg]], [[Russia]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.rian.ru/business/20110802/165518448.html |title=Russia to propose Yekaterinburg as Expo 2020 venue &#124; Business &#124; RIA Novosti |publisher=En.rian.ru |date= |accessdate=2013-10-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bie-paris.org/site/en/articles/general-news/430-yekaterinburg-new-candidate-for-world-expo-2020.html|title=Yekaterinburg, new candidate for World Expo 2020|accessdate=29 October 2011}}</ref>
* {{flagicon|Brazil}} [[São Paulo]], [[Brazil]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prefeitura.sp.gov.br/cidade/secretarias/relacoes_internacionais/noticias/?p=13802 |title=Portal da Prefeitura da Cidade de São Paulo |publisher=Prefeitura.sp.gov.br |date= |accessdate=2013-10-02}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bie-paris.org/site/en/articles/general-news/431-sao-paulo-new-candidate-for-world-expo-2020.html|title=Sao Paulo, new candidate for World Expo 2020|accessdate=29 October 2011}}</ref>
* {{flagicon|UAE}} [[Dubai]], [[United Arab Emirates]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.berlingske.dk/article/20080612/koebenhavn/80612042/ |title=København vil huse verdensudstilling &#124; www.b.dk |publisher=Berlingske.dk |date= |accessdate=2013-10-02}}</ref>
São Paulo was eliminated from contention after the first round of votes. Izmir was knocked out in the second. Yekaterinburg lost to Dubai in the third and final round of voting.

===Dubai Expo===
UAE selected the theme "Connecting Minds, Creating the Future", sub-themes being Sustainability, Mobility and Opportunity.<ref>{{cite web|author=Maeve Hosea |url=http://vision.ae/en/articles/expo_2020_dubai_celebrates_in_style |title=Dubai World Expo 2020: Dubai celebrates in style |website=vision.ae |publisher=Vision Magazine |date=2013-11-28 |accessdate=2015-09-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=His Highness Sheikh Ahmed bin Saeed Al Maktoum January 2015|url=http://vision.ae/en/articles/world_expo_from_vision_to_victory |title=Dubai World Expo 2020: From vision to victory |website=vision.ae |publisher=Vision Magazine |date=January 2014 |accessdate=2015-09-19}}</ref>

"In today’s highly interconnected world, a renewed vision of progress and development based on shared purpose and commitment is key. While a married human mind, an individual country, or a specific community is both unique and remarkable, it is by working collaboratively that we truly advance." Dubai Ruler [[Sheikh Mohammed bin Rashid Al Maktoum]] said in support of the bid.

The World Expo in Dubai in 2020 will be the first to be held in the [[MENA]] & SA (Middle East and North Africa & South Asia) region.
On 27 November 2013, when Dubai won the right to host the expo 2020, fireworks erupted at the world's tallest building, [[Burj Khalifa]]. A national holiday was declared the following day for all educational institutions across the country. The Dubai Ruler promised Dubai would "astonish the world," in 2020. The staging of the world fair and the preparations leading up to it are expected to result in 277,000 new jobs in the UAE, an injection of nearly $40 billion into the economy, and an increase in visitors of at least 25 million and up to 100 million.<ref name="Expo 2020 Dubai">{{cite web|title=Dubai wins right to host Expo 2020|url=http://gulfnews.com/business/economy/dubai-expo-2020-would-support-277-000-jobs-1.1181465|accessdate=28 November 2013|publisher=Gulf News}}</ref> Director General of Dubai Municipality, Hussain Nasser Lootah, said that they have the largest laboratory in the region, and can easily research new materials and technologies required for construction.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emirates247.com/business/economy-finance/dubai-is-ready-to-deal-with-expo-2020-construction-boom-lootah-2014-11-19-1.570636 |title=Dubai is ready to deal with Expo 2020 construction boom: Lootah - Emirates 24&#124;7 |work=Emirates247.com |date=2014-11-19 |accessdate=2015-09-19}}</ref> The world's tallest commercial tower to be built in Dubai, in [[Jumeirah Lake Towers]], was given the name "Burj 2020" in honour of the World Expo 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dmcc.ae/content-page?Turner-to-Project-Manage-Burj2020&articleid=a051000000UWFsnAAH|title=Turner to Project Manage Burj 2020|publisher=DMCC|access-date=2017-02-03}}</ref>

===Yekaterinburg Expo===
The Russian bid ''The Global Mind'' would have run from May 1 to October 31, and would have been the second largest expo (after [[Expo 2010|2010]] in Shanghai) and intended to  "survey world opinion through seven universal questions".<ref name="Ekaterinburg">{{cite web|url=http://www.bie-paris.org/site/en/ekaterinburg-russia|accessdate=17 November 2013|title=Ekaterinburg - Russia}}</ref>

===İzmir Expo===
The Turkish bid had a theme of ''New Routes to a Better World / Health for All'' and would have run from April 30 to October 31.<ref name="bieizmir">{{cite web|url=http://www.bie-paris.org/site/en/izmir-turkey|accessdate=18 November 2013|title=Izmir - Turkey}}</ref> A ''Health for All'' symnposium was held in October 2013 for BIE delegates and was to discuss health issues across the world.<ref name="h4asymposium">{{cite web|url=http://www.expoizmir.org.tr/124-health-for-all-symposium-exponews2020izmir.aspx|accessdate=18 November 2013|title=Health For All Symposium|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203034410/http://www.expoizmir.org.tr/124-health-for-all-symposium-exponews2020izmir.aspx|archivedate=3 December 2013|df=}}</ref>

===São Paulo Expo===
A Brazilian expo would have been called ''Power of Diversity, Harmony for Growth'',<ref name="saopself">{{cite web|url=http://www.saopauloexpo2020.com.br/?page_id=718&lang=en|accessdate=28 November 2013|title=The theme  –  São Paulo Expo 2020}}</ref> run from May 15 to November 15 and would have covered 502 hectares.<ref name="biesaop">{{cite web|url=http://www.bie-paris.org/site/en/sao-paulo-brazil|accessdate=18 November 2013|title=Sao Paulo - Brazil}}</ref>

